post_text: Like so many of you, we’re distraught by the news of #JacobBlake in Kenosha, Wisconsin. We also find ourselves asking the question, “What can I do?” Check out these helpful graphics from @antiracismdaily for ways to take action and demand accountability for Jacob. For far too long, Black and Brown communities have been plagued by systemic racism and the result of years of inequality. Individually, and as an organization, we have a responsibility to stand up to injustice, to become co-conspirators of anti racism and dismantle the practices and policies that perpetuate an unjust world. And we must never waver in proclaiming #BlackLivesMatter

post_text: We just wrapped the opening and keynote sessions of our first ever virtual Summit. We were welcomed by UP’s CEO Veronica Conforme, heard from a panel of experts on anti racism in schools, and a phenomenal keynote by Dr. Tanji Reed Marshall. Dr. Marshall shared with us what RESPECT means and looks like working with students. That means providing Relevant, Responsive and Rigorous Education that Starts from a Premise that Every Child’s inTellect matters! “We must respect our students’ minds and their abilities!” Thank you Dr. Marshall, for pushing us to think deeper about how we become anti racist leaders in our classrooms and schools! We're ready to #levelUP this year, together for our kids!

The Special Education Coordinator is responsible for ensuring the Special Education Program at UP Academy is compliant with state and federal Special Education laws.

Specific Responsibilities

Collaborate with the Principal, Leadership Team, teachers, and related service providers, to manage activities relating to compliance with all state and federal special education regulations and Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act; Provide expertise and assistance regarding the implementation of state and federal Special Education laws for students with disabilities; Collaborate with the Principal and Leadership Team in providing FAPE, LRE, and specialized instruction and services for students with… More

While we begin the school year remotely, we are working hard to provide an in-person learning option as soon as possible, while still keeping students and families safe. Check out the video to learn more about UAB! The school year begins September 1st.

post_text: This year's new Boston school staff welcome might have looked a little different, but one thing will never change: everything we do starts and ends with our students. As we plan for the upcoming school year, the health and safety of our students, families and staff is top of mind. We recognize this year may be challenging, but we know our students and staff are ready to #riseUP. And together, as a community, we will #levelUP to reach our goals!

post_text: “I have had the privilege of working with the UAO family for the past few years as the Lawrence Academic Coach for the Network team, and I am so excited to be stepping into my new role as Principal! I've watched this team work together to build a school community where students feel safe and loved, and I have been inspired by the ways they have risen to the challenge of continuing to uphold the values of our community in this unprecedented time of remote learning. I have seen firsthand that the UAO team can do anything they put their minds to, and I am excited to work alongside them to take our school to the next level, building independent learners who grow and achieve their goals!” -Jessica Deimel, Principal, #UPAcademyOliver

post_text:
“For the past 9 years that Kelsey has been at UP, she has been fully dedicated to improving educational outcomes for ALL students. As a founding member of UP Academy Boston, Kelsey then went on to become a Dean of Curriculum and Instruction at #UPAcademyOliver. She then took on the principalship when we needed her the most and did a phenomenal job stabilizing the school and putting systems in place that made students happier, more joyful, and more successful. We are indebted to Kelsey, and are privileged to have worked with her all these years. We are happy that Kelsey will stay connected with us as she focuses on her family, working on just a couple of projects with the network.” -Veronica Conforme, CEO
P.S. Check out Kelsey and Finn sporting their matching UAO owl hats!

I have seen firsthand that the UAO team can do anything they put their minds to, and I am excited to work alongside them to take our school to the next level, building independent learners who grow and achieve their goals!” -Jessica Deimel, Principal, #UPAcademyOliver

post_text:
“For the past 9 years that Kelsey has been at UP, she has been fully dedicated to improving educational outcomes for ALL students. As a founding member of UP Academy Boston, Kelsey then went on to become a Dean of Curriculum and Instruction at #UPAcademyOliver. She then took on the principalship when we needed her the most and did a phenomenal job stabilizing the school and putting systems in place that made students happier, more joyful, and more successful. We are indebted to Kelsey, and are privileged to have worked with her all these years. We are happy that Kelsey will stay connected with us as she focuses on her family, working on just a couple of projects with the network.” -Veronica Conforme, CEO
P.S. Check out Kelsey and Finn sporting their matching UAO owl hats!

post_text: UP’s Chief Equity and Learning Officer, Tisha, offered this reflection on #Juneteenth: This year’s Juneteenth celebration takes on even more importance as Americans of all races are seeing how much black American lives, and history, have been ignored. The protests that have consumed America since George Floyd’s murder are a continuation of the Black community’s centuries-long fight for freedom, and it should be evident to all Americans how this revolutionary struggle is just as, if not more, defining as America’s liberation from British rule. As we think about the profound outcry for change and racial justice that are consuming our nation, and the growing appreciation of Juneteenth, some… More

post_text:
#UPAcademyDorchester's History Teacher Mr. Moraes shares the history and importance of #Juneteenth: On January 1, 1863, President Abraham Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which stated that enslaved Africans in Confederate states "shall be free." Two and a half years later, on June 19th, 1865, the Union Army marched into Texas to order that all owners of enslaved Africans were to release them at once.

The Emancipation Proclamation freed enslaved Africans in the Confederacy on paper. But, in reality, the ruling class- those who owned enslaved Africans- did not end the practice of slavery until they were pressured directly.

As we celebrate Juneteenth today, we are in the midst…

post_text: As an organization dedicated to educating our future leaders, it’s not lost on us the effect the past few weeks are having on our scholars and their families. We know that we must be explicit and overt in our anti-racism work, challenging the status quo and disrupting systems of oppression. We also know that we must challenge ourselves to do better and do more to end racism and protect Black and Brown lives. These are just a few of the action steps, strategies and practices UP is implementing to become a more equity-based, anti-racist organization.

post_text:
A message from UP to our scholars, their families, and our community: We see you. We hear you. We love you.
>>>>>>> master

For far too long, black and brown communities have been plagued by systemic racism and institutionalized systems of oppression. And we know that has led to extreme inequities for our students and their families. If we are serious about empowering our scholars to cultivate their sharp minds, share their kind hearts and find their path and potential, our black and brown students have to be able to breathe and live first. UP stands in solidarity with millions across the country condemning police brutality and racism. We can do better, we must do better and we will do better. We loudly proclaim: #BlackLivesMatter
text:
A message from UP to our scholars, their families, and our community: We see you. We hear you. We love you.

For far too long, black and brown communities have been plagued by systemic racism and institutionalized systems of oppression. And we know that has led to extreme inequities for our students and their families. If we are serious about empowering our scholars to cultivate their sharp minds, share their kind hearts and find their path and potential, our black and brown students have to be able to breathe and live first. UP stands in solidarity with millions across the country condemning police brutality and racism. We can do better, we must do better and we will do better. We loudly proclaim: #BlackLivesMatter

post_text: At UP, we value the opportunity for our scholars to get involved in causes they care deeply about. That’s why we created the Student Leadership Council, which aims to further strengthen the relationships our students have with their community, both in and out of school. The SLC brings together more than 30 students from all five UP schools. This select group of students not only spans two school districts, but also crosses geographic boundaries empowering them to become changemakers within their communities. Check back tomorrow to read how one of our scholars felt her voice was heard on the SLC. #riseUP

April 7 at 4:09 PM ·

When COVID-19 closed Massachusetts schools, Dan Adler (MA '17), a Milken Educator and science teacher at UP Academy Leonard in Lawrence, had to jump headfirst into the ocean of distance learning. He knew he had to educate himself before he'd be able to teach his students. Here's how he got up the distance learning curve.

There are many ways to contribute this #GivingTuesday. Read how Mahdi Mohamed, UP Academy Boston graduate, plans to give back to his community. ✨

“I hope to use what I learn to work in a hospital setting with strong community relations and make the same impact on students that [UP Academy Boston] had on me. A large part of creating that impact is providing the young people we work with opportunities to build confidence, learn about the challenges they will face, and how to overcome them, while simultaneously growing their worldview. If we’re able to do that then we might have just lit a nonexistent burn for knowledge and personal growth. I know that was definitely the case for me.”

August 23, 2017 at 12:42 PM ·

When UP Academy John F. Kennedy Middle School opens its doors next week for the brand new school year students are up for a treat and a challenge to DREAM BIG!

This week marks the culmination of a full month of Professional Development for UP's educators who are eager to welcome scholars back to school.

Fresh new paint with inviting colors will enhance the learning environment, a brand new principal is leading the way, and educators have worked diligently to not only create beautiful learning spaces, but to collaborate in a school community where students will feel welcomed and will be provided with the tools to excel.
